{"text": "theory. In analogy with Eq. 9, a solution to the Majorana equation Eq. 11 can be expanded\n\nin terms of plane wave solutions10,\n\n\u03c8(x, t) =\n\nZ\n\nd3p\n\n(2\u03c0)3p\n\n2Ep\n\nX\n\ns\n\n[bs(p)us(p)e\u2212ipx+iEt + b\u2020\n\ns(p)Cu\u2217\n\ns(p)eipx\u2212iEt].\n\n(12)\n\nThe field in Eq. 12 satisfies the Majorana self-conjugacy relation \u03c8 = \u03c8(c) (charge neutral\n\nparticle that is identical to its own antiparticle). More importantly, only one kind of creation\n\noperator b\u2020\n\ns(p) operator appears in the field equation as opposed to separate and electron\n\nand positron operators as in Eq. 9. An alternative way to see that the Majorana equation\n\nEq. 11 involves half the degrees of freedom (i.e. does not have a separate hole degree of\n\nfreedom) is to use the Weyl representation of the \u03b3 matrices in Eq. 5. In this representation\n\nthe \u03b3 matrices are block off-diagonal (see Eq. 5) and the charge conjugation matrix C is\n\npurely block diagonal so that the bottom two components of the Majorana equation Eq. 11\n\ncan be written in terms of a two-component spinor \u03c9:\n\n\u0304\u03c3\u03bc\u2202\u03bc\u03c9 + m\u03c32\u03c9\u2217= 0.,\n\n(13)\n\nwhere \u0304\u03c3\u03bc = [I2, \u2212\u03c31, \u2212\u03c32, \u2212\u03c33]. The full four component Majorana spinor satisfying Eq. 10\n\nand 13 is obtained as \u03c8T(x) = (\u03c9T, (i\u03c32\u03c9)T).\n\nThe twin properties of charge neutrality and the identification of the particle with its\n\nown antiparticle are not particularly uncommon among bosons, with photons and \u03c00-mesons\n\nbeing two examples. In fact, as is well known4, the Fourier expansion of the photon field\n\nA\u03bc(x) also contains creation and annihilation operators of only one kind, a\u03bb(p) and a\u2020\n\n\u03bb(p),\n\nwhich is similar to the Fourier expansion in Eq. 12, because photon is a boson that is identical\n\nto its own antiparticle. This is not counter-intuitive in bosons, which are considered as fields\n\n5\n\nin the classical limits rather than particles. But these properties are quite special among\n\nfermions, which are considered as particles in the classical limit.", "embedding": [0.0077550802, -0.0071864463, 0.024708215, -0.0372885, 0.027544802, 0.0007881142, -0.0056761764, -0.009348705, -0.02209842, 0.07753272, 0.039425235, 0.017172491, 0.020320408, -0.0662302, -0.052208845, 0.0019082315, -0.007930534, -0.021945367, -0.07027978, 0.04711717, 0.008170899, 0.012476064, -0.07134565, -0.013410364, -0.015994964, 0.03718509, 0.0129247885, 0.05376034, 0.044367176, 0.021278407, 0.04155412, -0.0043663066, 0.026838, -0.05191983, 0.00023830985, 0.02270129, 0.016193481, -0.02654289, 0.051474325, -0.004704962, 0.072328754, -0.00075654197, 0.0384285, -0.02062077, -0.06580701, -0.0052948403, -0.053535163, -0.002715542, -0.04574302, -0.07105823, 0.025520287, -0.008509791, 0.037846524, -0.021002997, -0.01748564, -0.041164257, 0.027749157, 0.009574375, -0.019097364, 0.01478427, 0.013984243, -0.017282719, 0.0033524993, -0.045316238, -0.025632532, 0.055047017, 0.017625501, 0.05190276, 0.0057528764, -0.037731357, -0.018613167, 0.0060829255, -0.021989578, 0.03620358, -0.04311619, 0.040585544, -0.004411149, -0.040335037, -0.07284807, -0.0009938006, -0.01960675, -0.00586769, -0.041731928, 0.016861422, -0.008520042, -0.0125931315, -0.0063192477, -0.014854872, 0.015412244, 0.012763323, 0.0074292086, 0.050421417, -0.011310498, 0.011872882, 0.06889201, 0.017481865, 0.008760291, 0.022499925, 0.038568664, 0.0016785829, 0.033443272, 0.029407749, 0.004209282, 0.05913015, -0.022543678, 0.062148064, -0.02292437, 0.04424181, -0.022162808, -0.058185607, 0.036248602, -0.027030703, 0.04517184, 0.015018965, 0.016612304, 0.046156608, 0.02463589, 0.02322303, -0.06364662, -0.040696565, 0.011682262, 0.014317975, 0.05070402, -0.0049230075, -0.013937352, -0.014914979, 0.005768523, 0.046942167, -0.064878225, 0.009164832, 0.024119891, -0.01579253, -0.0026835708, 0.014578286, -0.04750441, 0.